76561197966526680,Recommended,418250,21992767,"Posted: 22 March, 2016",all,Saracen26,"One word... Fantasic, absolutely fantastic!Ok, that's 2 words.In all seriousness though, Polaris Sector does something that no other Space 4X game has done in years. It simplifies the rubbish often found in 4X games, and also adds a new twist on the genre's often seen staples.My favourite Real Time 4X (and overall PC title) game has always been Imperium Galactica 2. Polaris Sector comes a close 2nd. Whilst it may not have an implemented storyline or the polish of IG2. It's unique enough to hold its own ground in a very solid manner. The UI is very well implemented as not to confuse the mechanics and the general gameplay is easy enough to follow without having to concern yourself with a Distant Worlds: Universe kind of depth.Some may be turned off with the slow burn of the game, as depending on how many races you place into the game and the number of systems, a single game can take many many hours. But since this game does have 9 races, as well as the ability to customise these races, plus a number of galaxy types.. With the added bonus of random generation, this game's replay value can be considered immense, and this is well worth the asking price!All in all, as a verteran of the 4X genre, this is a game I could highly recommend. Whilst it could likely do with more random encounters and some elements of a storyline to increase the lore of the entire universe further. It certainly wins my personal reccomendation."
76561197971515855,Not Recommended,418250,22091708,"Posted: 27 March, 2016",all,IntelJoe,"It looks fun, but really it looks like a game for people that are waiting for Stellaris. There are also a lot of UI issues, and for the most part the game feels like it could be a real good game but falls short in several area's (ship designer, empire management, etc). Honestly this game made me want to Space Empires 4. It just doesn't get the right information to the player, it feels wonky and clunky like they weren't sure what would work.EDIT:Polaris Sector feels like it took a lot of idea's from different 4x games (Space Empires 4, Master of Orion, Stellaris. etc). This is what attracted me to it.The strategic screen looks like that of the upcoming game Stelaris but doesn't have that polished look. I feel like the game tries hard to get the correct information to the player but falls short and the UI just feels smushed and not clear. For example the resource panel on the strategic screen are stuck in a box and only have the icons with current production levels. There is no explanation as to what resources are what, no sense of how a deficit in one resource impacts or doesn't impact the player. I also feel that there is a lack of information given to the player about what buildings to build and planet management. The descriptions don't actually convey what the benefit or loss of building one building or another is. I very much had to guess that one building was a military building and so on from the description with no real idea of what it actually does. Also the amount of buildings you can build is not explicitly stated and I found myself fumbling with what to build and why. The ship designer also feels the same way, that I am not sure what to use and where and how much of specific parts. I found it repetitive, boring, and frustrating. The research tree I found as a black hole, basically just a big giant pile of stuff to research with no real goal in sight other than ""something"" that I assumed was better than whatever I had. I understand they were going for a feel that was for focusing on a certain research path and it would reveal techs related to that path in no specific order but I feel this was the biggest pitfall. Not because this was a bad idea but because of how it was implemented. The research is not really searchable, I'd have to get through 2-3 or more clicks before I would get to a description that really only describes a technology and doesn't tell me why it would benefit me. So I would search the descriptions of the varied researches available looking for something like ""shields"" or ""phasers"" but after about 10 minutes of searching, it was the last straw and gave up then asked for a refund.Overall it feels like it could be a lot better, but it lacks some basic functionality. Like hovering your mouse over for tool tips. Or searching the tech tree. Or the game telling you what to do and why. I have no problem trying to figure out how these things work, but when I feel like I ""need"" to read the manual or play a tutorial in order to get the basic fundamentals of a game that maybe it wasn't put together well in the first place.Also the main menu screen has no ""Options"" menu (or at least it wasn't obvious to me) and the music is terrible and too loud, I wanted to shut it off immediately but I couldn't. So I rushed through an empire creation to get in game so I could merely shut off the music."
